{"title_page": "Sarah Aarons", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Sarah Aarons\n| background = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1994|10|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Melbourne]], Australia\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Dance music|dance]]\n* [[Rock music|rock]]\n}}\n| occupation = Songwriter\n| label = [[Sony/ATV Music Publishing|Sony ATV Publishing]]\n}}\n\n'''Sarah Paige Aarons''' (born 4 October 1994, previously known as '''Paige IV''' and sometimes simply as '''Sarah''') is a songwriter from Melbourne, Australia. Now based in Los Angeles,<ref>{{cite web|title=For Sarah Aarons, illness was a 'turning point' on the way to a chart-topping song|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-15/sarah-aarons-songwriter-stay-us-number-one-zedd-alessia-cara/8668280}}</ref> Aarons is signed to [[Sony/ATV Music Publishing|Sony ATV Publishing]]. She co-wrote \"[[Stay (Zedd and Alessia Cara song)|Stay]]\" by [[Zedd]] and [[Alessia Cara]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Meet the 23-year-old Melbourne writer behind the biggest pop song in the US|url=http://www.theindustryobserver.com.au/meet-23-year-old-melbourne-writer-behind-biggest-pop-song-us/}}</ref> and \"[[The Middle (Zedd, Maren Morris and Grey song)|The Middle]]\" by Zedd, [[Maren Morris]] and [[Grey (duo)|Grey]], which both went to #1 on [[Mainstream Top 40]] and were each certified double platinum in the US. In 2019 Aarons was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] at the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards]] for her work on \"The Middle\".\n\nIn Australia, Aarons had acclaimed success with the breakout song \"[[Keeping Score (song)|Keeping Score]]\" by [[L D R U|LDRU]],<ref>{{cite web|title=The Secrets Behind How Australia's Biggest Pop Tracks Get Made|url=http://junkee.com/longform/secrets-behind-australias-biggest-pop-tracks-get-made}}</ref> \"Frozen\" by Pon Cho and [[Cosmo's Midnight]]'s \"History,\" which in turn has become the most played song on [[Triple J]] in 2017. She has also received three ARIA Awards for her work with LDRU and has gone double platinum in Australia.\n \nRecently, Aarons was appointed one of APRA AMCOS Ambassadors<ref>{{cite web|title=10 quick questions with Ambassador Sarah Aarons|url=http://apraamcos.com.au/news/2017/october/10-quick-questions-with-ambassador-sarah-aarons/}}</ref> and was included in ''LA Weekly''{{'}}s 20 hottest current songwriters.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 20 Hottest Songwriters in Pop Music Right Now|url=http://www.laweekly.com/music/the-20-best-pop-songwriters-in-2017-8763662}}</ref> At the [[APRA Music Awards of 2018]] she won Breakthrough Songwriter of the Year,<ref name=\"APRAWinners 2018\">{{cite web | title = Full List of Winners | url = http://apraamcos.com.au/awards/2018-awards/apra-music-awards/full-list-of-winners/ | publisher = [[Australasian Performing Right Association]] (APRA) &#124; [[Australasian Mechanical Copyright Owners Society]] (AMCOS) | accessdate = 13 April 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"BRSotYNom 2018\">{{cite web | url = http://apraamcos.com.au/awards/2018-awards/apra-music-awards/breakthrough-songwriter-of-the-year/ | title = Breakthrough Songwriter of the Year | publisher = Australasian Performing Right Association (APRA) &#124; Australasian Mechanical Copyright Owners Society (AMCOS) | year = 2018 | accessdate = 14 April 2018 }}</ref> she was also nominated for Country Work of the Year for the track, \"House\", alongside co-writers [[Brooke McClymont]], Mollie McClymont, [[Samantha McClymont]] and Michael Fatkin.<ref name=\"CWotYNom 2018\">{{cite web | url = http://apraamcos.com.au/awards/2018-awards/apra-music-awards/country/ | title = Country Work of the Year | publisher = Australasian Performing Right Association (APRA) &#124; Australasian Mechanical Copyright Owners Society (AMCOS) | year = 2018 | accessdate = 14 April 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAt the 2019 APRA Awards, Aarons won Songwriter of the Year as well as Most Played Australian Work, Rock Work of the Year and Dance Work of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sarah Aarons, Amy Shark, Dean Lewis Win Big at 2019 APRA Awards|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8509360/sarah-aarons-amy-shark-dean-lewis-win-big-at-2019-apra-awards}}</ref>\n\n==Selected discography==\n{{Color box|#ffffcc|border=darkgray}} indicates a background vocal contribution.\n\n{{Color box|#87CEEB|border=darkgray}} indicates an un-credited lead vocal contribution.\n\n{{Color box|#6495ed|border=darkgray}} indicates a credited vocal/featured artist contribution.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Year !! Artist !! Album !! Song !! Co-written with\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2015 || Smizzy || ''The Cover'' ||style=\"background:#6495ed\"| \"Problems Aside\"<br>{{small|(featuring Paige IV)}} || Martin Brown, Luke Rundle, Timothy Carr, Paul Conrad\n|-\n| [[LDRU]] || ''Sizzlar'' ||style=\"background:#6495ed\"| \"[[Keeping Score (song)|Keeping Score]]\"<br>{{small|(featuring Paige IV)}} || [[LDRU|Drew Carmody]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"| 2016 || rowspan=\"2\"| [[Jai Waetford]] || rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Heart Miles]]'' ||style=\"background:#ffffcc\"| \"Living Not Dreaming\" || [[Jai Waetford]], Michael Fatkin\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ffffcc\"| \"Worlds\" || [[Jai Waetford]], Michael Fatkin\n|-\n| PON CHO || rowspan=\"3\" {{n/a|Non-album single}} ||style=\"background:#6495ed\"| \"Lonely Walls\"<br>{{small|(featuring Paige IV)}} || Kevin Kerr\n|-\n| Emmalyn || \"Hungover\" || Emmalyn Estrada, [[Leland (musician)|Brett McLaughlin]], Jordan Palmer\n|-\n| PON CHO ||style=\"background:#6495ed\"| \"Frozen\"<br>{{small|(featuring Paige IV)}} || Kevin Kerr\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\"| 2017 || [[Cosmo's Midnight]] || ''What Comes Next'' ||style=\"background:#87ceeb\"| \"History\" || [[Cosmo's Midnight|Cosmo Liney]], [[Cosmo's Midnight|Patrick Liney]]\n|-\n| [[Lost Kings]] || {{n/a|Non-album single}} || \"Quit You\"<br>{{small|(featuring [[Tinashe]])}} || [[Lost Kings|Robert Abisi]