{"title_page": "Operation World", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{ref improve|date=July 2014}}\n{{third-party|date=July 2014}}\n{{external links|date=November 2015}}\n}}\n{{Infobox book\n| italic title   = <!--(see above)-->\n| name           = Operation World\n| image          = Operation World.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| author         = Patrick Johnstone\n| illustrator    = \n| cover_artist   = \n| country        = \n| language       = English\n| series         = \n| release_number = \n| subject        = \n| published      = 1974 (Dorothea Mission)\n| pub_date       = \n| english_pub_date = \n| media_type     = \n| pages          = \n| awards         = \n| isbn           = 1-85078-007-2\n| isbn_note      = \n| dewey          = \n| congress       = \n| notes          =\n| exclude_cover  = \n| website        =\n}}\n'''''Operation World''''' is a reference book and [[prayer]] guide, begun by Patrick Johnstone and continued by Jason Mandryk, both from [[WEC International]], a [[Christian mission]] agency.  The first edition was published by Dorothea Mission, later editions by [[Send the Light]], publishing branch of [[Operation Mobilisation]] (OM). The latest edition of ''Operation World'' was published by [[Biblica]], but is now distributed by InterVarsity Press<ref>http://www.ivpress.com</ref> (IVP) after IVP acquired the publishing arm of Biblica<ref>{{cite web |author = Alisse Wissman |title = InterVarsity Press Acquires Biblica Books |url = http://www.biblica.com/uploads/news-and-press/Biblica-Books-Press-Release-Nov-17-2011_11_22_2011_786.pdf |publisher = InterVarsity Press (IVP) |location = [[Westmont, Illinois]], [[United States]] |date = 17 November 2011 |accessdate = 6 April 2012 |quote = Westmont, IL\u2014InterVarsity Press (IVP), a leading publisher of thoughtful Christian books, is pleased to announce that it has entered into a definitive agreement to acquire Biblica Books, the book-publishing arm of Biblica Worldwide. }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> in late 2011. ''Operation World'' content has been made available online<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://besturdubook.com/|title=Best Urdu books {{!}} Read and download Urdu Books .|website=Best Urdu Books|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> through GMI (Global Mapping International)<ref>http://www.GMI.org</ref>. It is aimed at informing Christians about every country in the world in order to encourage the [[Christian Church|church]] to [[prayer|pray]] for the world and to engage the world in Christian mission. This resource is written from an [[evangelical Christian]] point of view, and the Operation World team is now led by Jason Mandryk and Molly Wall. \n\n''Operation World'' was on the list of the 50 most influential evangelical books in [[Christianity Today]] magazine. It is intended to mobilize the church to effective intercession and world mission and ultimately, to help the global Church fulfil the [[Great Commission]].\n\n''Operation World'' has been published in seven editions. The most recent is the 2010 edition, released in October 2010,<ref>Jason Mandryk, \"Operation World,\" Biblica Publishing, 2010</ref> the first major update since the 2001 edition.<ref>Patrick Johnstone, Jason Mandryk, and Robyn Johnstone, \"Operation World: 21st Century Edition, Waynesboro: Paternoster, 2001.</ref> The original edition was produced in 1974 by Patrick Johnstone, a missionary in South Africa, as a 32-page booklet of basic information about 30 countries. ''Operation World'' has been translated into several other languages: Spanish, French, Dutch, German, Portuguese, Russian, Korean, Indonesian, and simplified Chinese. Parts of ''Operation World'' have been translated into Arabic, Urdu, and Czech. The cumulative number of copies printed in all languages exceeds 2.5 million. In the missionary tradition of the Dorothea Mission and WEC International, the team behind the production of ''Operation World'' consists only of volunteers (i.e., no salaried staff). Currently Molly and Jason are the only full time volunteers in the Operation World team.\n\nThe 1,000-plus page prayer resource is also organized as a calendar-year daily prayer guide. Each 3- to 4-page daily section begins with basic information on a country\u2019s geography, demographics, population, literacy, economy, etc. ''Operation World'' then gives a breakdown of percentage of religions, Christian denominations, and missions groups, followed by points for prayer. These prayer points are directed toward the social, political, economic, cultural, and religious life of each nation, as well as life and activity of the existing Church in each country.\n\nThematically, ''Operation World'' begins with global issues and world missions, then narrows to cover the six continents before it settles into a country-by-country format, covering every nation and autonomous territory.\n\nData is gathered from sources including primary input from national Christian church leaders, missionaries, and researchers. A consultative process is used, eliciting input and response from nearly 2,000 such contacts in every part of the world. Information is also gathered from more than 200 periodicals and journals, the plethora of news agencies, websites of churches and ministries around the world, and more encyclopedic resources such as the World Christian Database<ref>http://www.worldchristiandatabase.org</ref>, the [[Ethnologue]]<ref>http://www.ethnologue.org/</ref>, and the [[Joshua Project]]. The ''Operation World'' database includes information on approximately 33,000 Christian denominations, 16 major religions, 1,200 missions agencies, and 16,000 fields of ministry.\n\nAdditional ''Operation World'' resources include the book in paperback, CD, DVD or ebook formats, individual country profiles and prayer maps and are all available from [http://www.operationworld.com InterVarsity Press].\n\nOther resources produced by the Operation World team include:\n\n''Pray for the World'', an abridged and [[simplified English]]{{dn|date=August 2019}} version of ''Operation World'', and was published in 2015 by IVP. ''Pray for the World'' was published for the purpose of greater engagement with those who may not be inclined to use a 1000+ page reference volume. It is easier to read for non-native English speakers, more affordable due to smaller size, and a more feasible project for translation. Thus far, it has been translated into Chinese, Korean, Indonesian, Spanish, Portuguese, Urdu, Hindi, Russian, Arabic, and Amharic. \n\n''Window on the World'', the children's version of ''Operation World''. ''Window on the World'' began life as ''You Can Change the World'', written by Patrick Johnstone's late first wife, Jill and published in 1992. A followup volume, ''You Too Can Change the World'', was completed by Daphne Spraggett, using Jill's unfinished work. These two volumes became a compendium in 2001, with the new name ''Window on the World''. The 2nd edition, released in October 2018 was edited by Molly Wall and Jason Mandryk and published by IVP in the USA and by Lion Hudson<ref>http://www.lionhudson.com/</ref> in the UK.\n\nOperation World also produces a free [[mobile app]]<ref>http://www.operationworld.org/prayer-app/</ref>, and a weekly church bulletin<ref>http://www.lausanne.org/pray</ref> in a collaborative partnership with the [[Lausanne Movement]]<ref>http://www.lausanne.org/</ref>.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.operationworld.org/ Operation World online]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101116154236/http://www.missionbooks.org/operation-world/ Operation World / Mission Books]\n* [http://www.gmi.org GMI (Global Mapping International)]\n* [http://www.ibsdirect.com/c-98-biblica-books.aspx?sections=,619, Biblica Publishing site for Operation World]\n* [http://www.wecinternational.org WEC International]\n\n[[Category:Christian missions]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{ref improve|date=July 2014}}\n{{third-party|date=July 2014}}\n{{external links|date=November 2015}}\n}}\n{{Infobox book\n| italic title   = <!--(see above)-->\n| name           = Operation World\n| image          = Operation World.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| author         = Patrick Johnstone\n| illustrator    = \n| cover_artist   = \n| country        = \n| language       = English\n| series         = \n| release_number = \n| subject        = \n| published      = 1974 (Dorothea Mission)\n| pub_date       = \n| english_pub_date = \n| media_type     = \n| pages          = \n| awards         = \n| isbn           = 1-85078-007-2\n| isbn_note      = \n| dewey          = \n| congress       = \n| notes          =\n| exclude_cover  = \n| website        =\n}}\n'''''Operation World''''' is a reference book and [[prayer]] guide, begun by Patrick Johnstone and continued by Jason Mandryk, both from [[WEC International]], a [[Christian mission]] agency.  The first edition was published by Dorothea Mission, later editions by [[Send the Light]], publishing branch of [[Operation Mobilisation]] (OM). The latest edition of ''Operation World'' was published by [[Biblica]], but is now distributed by InterVarsity Press<ref>http://www.ivpress.com</ref> (IVP) after IVP acquired the publishing arm of Biblica<ref>{{cite web |author = Alisse Wissman |title = InterVarsity Press Acquires Biblica Books |url = http://www.biblica.com/uploads/news-and-press/Biblica-Books-Press-Release-Nov-17-2011_11_22_2011_786.pdf |publisher = InterVarsity Press (IVP) |location = [[Westmont, Illinois]], [[United States]] |date = 17 November 2011 |accessdate = 6 April 2012 |quote = Westmont, IL\u2014InterVarsity Press (IVP), a leading publisher of thoughtful Christian books, is pleased to announce that it has entered into a definitive agreement to acquire Biblica Books, the book-publishing arm of Biblica Worldwide. }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> in late 2011. ''Operation World'' content has been made available online<ref>http://www.operationworld.org</ref> through GMI (Global Mapping International)<ref>http://www.GMI.org</ref>. It is aimed at informing Christians about every country in the world in order to encourage the [[Christian Church|church]] to [[prayer|pray]] for the world and to engage the world in Christian mission. This resource is written from an [[evangelical Christian]] point of view, and the Operation World team is now led by Jason Mandryk and Molly Wall. \n\n''Operation World'' was on the list of the 50 most influential evangelical books in [[Christianity Today]] magazine. It is intended to mobilize the church to effective intercession and world mission and ultimately, to help the global Church fulfil the [[Great Commission]].\n\n''Operation World'' has been published in seven editions. The most recent is the 2010 edition, released in October 2010,<ref>Jason Mandryk, \"Operation World,\" Biblica Publishing, 2010</ref> the first major update since the 2001 edition.<ref>Patrick Johnstone, Jason Mandryk, and Robyn Johnstone, \"Operation World: 21st Century Edition, Waynesboro: Paternoster, 2001.</ref> The original edition was produced in 1974 by Patrick Johnstone, a missionary in South Africa, as a 32-page booklet of basic information about 30 countries. ''Operation World'' has been translated into several other languages: Spanish, French, Dutch, German, Portuguese, Russian, Korean, Indonesian, and simplified Chinese. Parts of ''Operation World'' have been translated into Arabic, Urdu, and Czech. The cumulative number of copies printed in all languages exceeds 2.5 million. In the missionary tradition of the Dorothea Mission and WEC International, the team behind the production of ''Operation World'' consists only of volunteers (i.e., no salaried staff). Currently Molly and Jason are the only full time volunteers in the Operation World team.\n\nThe 1,000-plus page prayer resource is also organized as a calendar-year daily prayer guide. Each 3- to 4-page daily section begins with basic information on a country\u2019s geography, demographics, population, literacy, economy, etc. ''Operation World'' then gives a breakdown of percentage of religions, Christian denominations, and missions groups, followed by points for prayer. These prayer points are directed toward the social, political, economic, cultural, and religious life of each nation, as well as life and activity of the existing Church in each country.\n\nThematically, ''Operation World'' begins with global issues and world missions, then narrows to cover the six continents before it settles into a country-by-country format, covering every nation and autonomous territory.\n\nData is gathered from sources including primary input from national Christian church leaders, missionaries, and researchers. A consultative process is used, eliciting input and response from nearly 2,000 such contacts in every part of the world. Information is also gathered from more than 200 periodicals and journals, the plethora of news agencies, websites of churches and ministries around the world, and more encyclopedic resources such as the World Christian Database<ref>http://www.worldchristiandatabase.org</ref>, the [[Ethnologue]]<ref>http://www.ethnologue.org/</ref>, and the [[Joshua Project]]. The ''Operation World'' database includes information on approximately 33,000 Christian denominations, 16 major religions, 1,200 missions agencies, and 16,000 fields of ministry.\n\nAdditional ''Operation World'' resources include the book in paperback, CD, DVD or ebook formats, individual country profiles and prayer maps and are all available from [http://www.operationworld.com InterVarsity Press].\n\nOther resources produced by the Operation World team include:\n\n''Pray for the World'', an abridged and [[simplified English]]{{dn|date=August 2019}} version of ''Operation World'', and was published in 2015 by IVP. ''Pray for the World'' was published for the purpose of greater engagement with those who may not be inclined to use a 1000+ page reference volume. It is easier to read for non-native English speakers, more affordable due to smaller size, and a more feasible project for translation. Thus far, it has been translated into Chinese, Korean, Indonesian, Spanish, Portuguese, Urdu, Hindi, Russian, Arabic, and Amharic. \n\n''Window on the World'', the children's version of ''Operation World''. ''Window on the World'' began life as ''You Can Change the World'', written by Patrick Johnstone's late first wife, Jill and published in 1992. A followup volume, ''You Too Can Change the World'', was completed by Daphne Spraggett, using Jill's unfinished work. These two volumes became a compendium in 2001, with the new name ''Window on the World''. The 2nd edition, released in October 2018 was edited by Molly Wall and Jason Mandryk and published by IVP in the USA and by Lion Hudson<ref>http://www.lionhudson.com/</ref> in the UK.\n\nOperation World also produces a free [[mobile app]]<ref>http://www.operationworld.org/prayer-app/</ref>, and a weekly church bulletin<ref>http://www.lausanne.org/pray</ref> in a collaborative partnership with the [[Lausanne Movement]]<ref>http://www.lausanne.org/</ref>.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.operationworld.org/ Operation World online]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101116154236/http://www.missionbooks.org/operation-world/ Operation World / Mission Books]\n* [http://www.gmi.org GMI (Global Mapping International)]\n* [http://www.ibsdirect.com/c-98-biblica-books.aspx?sections=,619, Biblica Publishing site for Operation World]\n* [http://www.wecinternational.org WEC International]\n\n[[Category:Christian missions]]\n", "name_user": "Mazca", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Reverted edits by39.50.90.20(talk) to last version by Shahzadlawa5544)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operation_World"}
{"title_page": "2014 Andy Murray tennis season", "text_new": "{{infobox tennis player season\n|image                 = Roland Garros 20140529 Andy Murray 2.jpg\n|caption               = Murray competing at the French Open\n|fullname              = Andy Murray\n|country               = {{nowrap|{{GBR2}}}}\n|singlesrecord         = {{tennis record|won=59|lost=20}}\n|singlestitles         = 3\n|calendarprizemoney    =\n|yearendsinglesranking = No. 6\n|singlesrankingchange  = {{tennis ranking change|new=6|old=4}} <!-- Ranking from previous year: #4 -->\n|AustralianOpenresult  = QF\n|FrenchOpenresult      = SF\n|Wimbledonresult       = QF\n|USOpenresult          = QF\n|Othertournaments      = yes\n|MastersCupresult      = RR\n|Olympicsresult        =\n|doublesrecord         = {{tennis record|won=3|lost=2}}\n|doublestitles         = 0\n|yearenddoublesranking =\n|currentdoublesranking = No. 330\n|doublesrankingchange  = {{tennis ranking change|new=330|old=108}} <!-- Ranking from previous year: #108 -->\n|grandslamsdoublesresults =\n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult =\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult     =\n|WimbledonDoublesresult      =\n|USOpenDoublesresult         =\n|OthertournamentsDoubles     = <!-- adds a \"Other doubles tournaments\" title -->\n|MastersCupDoublesresult     =\n|OlympicsDoublesresult       =\n|Mixed                       = <!-- adds mixed information-->\n|mixedrecord =\n|mixedtitles =\n|AustralianOpenMixedresult =\n|FrenchOpenMixedresult =\n|WimbledonMixedresult =\n|USOpenMixedresult =\n|OthertournamentsMixedDoubles =\n|OlympicMixedDoublesresult =\n|Daviscup = Y\n|Daviscupresult = QF\n|Injury = <!-- add injuries with date/interval, type of injury in brackets and reference if available -->\n|Notes = <!-- general important notes and/or anything that has changed from previous season: change of coach, equipment, ...etc -->\n|updated = {{date|2014-11-15}}\n}}\n{{Main|Andy Murray}}\n\nThe '''2014 Andy Murray tennis season''' began at the Qatar Open. He was defending titles in [[Miami Masters|Miami]] and at [[Queen's Club Championships|Queen's Club]], as well as at [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]. However, he failed to retain any of these, losing to [[Novak Djokovic]], [[Radek \u0160t\u011bp\u00e1nek]] and [[Grigor Dimitrov]] at each of these tournaments.\n\nHis form improved in the latter part of the season, as he won 3 titles in 5 weeks at [[ATP Shenzhen Open|Shenzhen]], [[Vienna Open|Vienna]] and [[Valencia Open 500|Valencia]]. This saw him finish the year ranked world number 6.\n\n==Yearly Summary==\n\n===Australian Open Series===\n\n====Qatar Open====\nMurray made his competitive return to the tour at the [[2014 Qatar ExxonMobil Open|Qatar Open]], having been out injured since undergoing back surgery in September 2013.<ref name=\"Qatar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/25560948|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray easily beats Mousa Zayed on competitive return|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> He faced local wildcard [[Mousa Shanan Zayed]] and took only 37 minutes to defeat him, not dropping a single game in the process.<ref name=\"Qatar\"/> He then suffered a shock defeat to [[Florian Mayer]] in the following round. Having been in a commanding position, Murray lost 12 of the last 15 games to crash out in three sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/25568166|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray loses to Florian Mayer at Qatar Open|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n====Australian Open====\nMurray then competed at the [[2014 Australian Open|Australian Open]]. He got his campaign underway in difficult conditions, with temperatures in excess of 40 degrees Celsius, against [[Go Soeda]] and saw him off in under 90 minutes, only dropping five games in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/25689984|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beats Go Soeda in Australian Open first round|author=Piers Newbery|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> He next faced qualifier [[Vincent Millot]] and again won in straight sets, recovering from 5\u20131 down in the third to take it 7\u20135 by winning 23 consecutive points from set point down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/25740207|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beats Vincent Millot at Australian Open|author=Piers Newbery|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> Murray's first serious test came from [[Feliciano L\u00f3pez]] but the top 30 player failed to trouble him as he secured another three set victory,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/25772348|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beats Lopez to reach Australian Open fourth round|author=Piers Newbery|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> to set up a fourth round clash with lucky loser [[St\u00e9phane Robert]]. Murray dropped his first set of the tournament in a third set tie-break but recovered to take the fourth and progress to the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/25798868|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray through to Australian Open quarter-finals|author=Piers Newbery|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> There he faced [[Roger Federer]], in their fifth meeting at a Grand Slam. Murray was unable to match Federer's level throughout most of the match and was defeated in four sets, ending his run of four consecutive Australian Open semi-finals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tennis/australian-open-2014-andy-murray-unable-to-stop-roger-federer-who-marches-on-to-semifinal-meeting-with-rafael-nadal-9076809.html|title=Australian Open 2014: Andy Murray unable to stop Roger Federer who marches on to semi-final meeting with Rafael Nadal|work=The Independent}}</ref>\n\n===Spring hardcourt season===\n\n====Davis Cup First round====\nMurray then represented [[Great Britain Davis Cup team|Great Britain]] in the [[2014 Davis Cup|Davis Cup]] against the [[United States Davis Cup team|United States]] in [[San Diego]]. He won both his singles rubbers, first defeating [[Donald Young (tennis)|Donald Young]]<ref name=\"USA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/25991795|title=BBC Sport - Davis Cup: James Ward & Andy Murray win in San Diego|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> and then securing the 3\u20131 victory on the Sunday with a win over [[Sam Querrey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/feb/02/great-britain-davis-cup-usa-andy-murray|title=Great Britain reach Davis Cup quarter-finals by beating United States|work=the Guardian}}</ref> It was the first time that Great Britain had reached the quarterfinals of the Davis Cup since 1986.<ref name=\"USA\"/>\n\n====Rotterdam Open====\nFollowing the Davis Cup tie, Murray travelled to [[Rotterdam]] to play in the [[2014 ABN AMRO World Tennis Tournament|Rotterdam Open]]. There he overcame [[\u00c9douard Roger-Vasselin]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaypost.com/sport/murray-wins-in-rotterdam-1.218664|title=SP Error messages - The Sunday Post - The website of Scotland's favourite family newspaper since 1914|work=sundaypost.com}}</ref> and [[Dominic Thiem]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/feb/13/andy-murray-dominic-thiem-rotterdam|title=Andy Murray made to struggle before beating world No113 Dominic Thiem|work=the Guardian}}</ref> to set up a quarter-final encounter with [[Marin \u010cili\u0107]]. Murray struggled against \u010cili\u0107, playing for the three consecutive days for the first time since surgery, and was unable to find his best form as he crashed out in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/26194542|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beaten by Marin Cilic in Rotterdam quarter-finals|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n====Mexican Open====\nAfter his defeat to \u010cili\u0107, Murray next chose to play in the [[2014 Abierto Mexicano Telcel|Mexican Open]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/tennis/news/12110/9183817/atp-mexican-open-andy-murray-back-in-action-in-acapulco|title=ATP Mexican Open: Andy Murray back in action in Acapulco|work=SkySports}}</ref> He recovered from a set down in his opener to defeat [[Pablo And\u00fajar]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/26349696|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beats Pablo Andujar in Mexican Open first round|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> and then overcame [[Jo\u00e3o Sousa]] to reach the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/tennis/news/12110/9186650/atp-mexican-open-andy-murray-makes-quarter-finals-in-acapulco|title=ATP Mexican Open: Andy Murray makes quarter-finals in Acapulco|work=SkySports}}</ref> Again, Murray failed to find his best form but still managed to record his 12th consecutive win over [[Gilles Simon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/26380204|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beats Gilles Simon in Mexican Open to reach semi-finals|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> In his first semi-final since winning Wimbledon the previous year, Murray suffered a three sets defeat to [[Grigor Dimitrov]]. Murray took the first set but then lost two close tie-breaks as Dimitorv recorded his first win over Murray.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/01/andy-murray-loses-grigor-dimitrov-acapulco-semi|title=Andy Murray suffers defeat to Grigor Dimitrov in Acapulco semi-final|work=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\n====Indian Wells Masters====\nMurray headed into the first [[ATP World Tour Masters 1000|Masters Series]] tournament of the year still struggling to find form. Matters failed to improve at the [[2014 BNP Paribas Open|Indian Wells Masters]] as he struggled past [[Luk\u00e1\u0161 Rosol]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/26501695|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray recovers to beat Lukas Rosol at Indian Wells|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> and [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Vesel\u00fd]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/10/andy-murray-jiri-vesely-indian-wells|title=Andy Murray blows hot and cold in win over Jiri Vesely at Indian Wells|work=the Guardian}}</ref> before being eliminated in the fourth round by [[Milos Raonic]] in a match where Murray admitted he ''\"wasn't good enough\"''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/12/andy-murray-milos-raonic-indian-wells|title=Andy Murray suffers shock defeat to Milos Raonic at Indian Wells|work=the Guardian}}</ref> Following the tournament, Murray mutually split with his coach [[Ivan Lendl]], ending their partnership after two years together.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/26646809|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray and coach Ivan Lendl agree mutual split|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nMurray offered to play with [[2012 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Doubles#Finals|2012 Wimbledon Doubles champion]] [[Jonathan Marray]] because Marray was unable to convince anyone to join him on court. Marray was struggling for full fitness and finding a regular doubles partner, travelling to tournaments with no plan whatsoever.<ref name=\"Wimbledon 2014: Jonny Marray's doubles trouble ends in win as he makes second round with John-Patrick Smith\">{{cite news |title= Wimbledon 2014: Jonny Marray's doubles trouble ends in win as he makes second round with John-Patrick Smith\n|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/wimbledon/10929416/Wimbledon-2014-Jonny-Marrays-doubles-trouble-ends-in-win-as-he-makes-second-round-with-John-Patrick-Smith.html/|publisher= Daily Mail|date= 26 June 2014}}</ref> \nAfter fans queued around the grounds to watch [[Roger Federer]] and [[Stanislas Wawrinka]] play together, it was standing room only for Murray and Marray's first competitive match together. Andy Murray and Jonny Marray won a thrilling doubles clash against [[Ga\u00ebl Monfils]] and [[Juan M\u00f3naco]] only to lose in the second round to the No 2 seeds [[Alexander Peya]] and [[Bruno Soares]].<ref name=\"Murray and Marray's Indian Wells doubles run ends after loss to Peya and Soares\n\">{{cite news |title= Murray and Marray's Indian Wells doubles run ends after loss to Peya and Soares\n|url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/tennis/article-2577038/Andy-Murray-Jonathan-Marray-lose-Alexander-Peya-Bruno-Soares-Indian-Wells.html/|publisher= Daily Mail|date= 9 March 2014}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}}\n\n====Miami Masters====\nAt the [[2014 Sony Open Tennis|Miami Masters]] Murray began his title defence with a win over [[Matthew Ebden]], recovering to take 12 of the last 13 games having lost the first set.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/26695849|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beats Matthew Ebden in Sony Open second round|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> Murray then turned in two of his better performances of the season to defeat [[Feliciano L\u00f3pez]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/26705843|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beats Feliciano Lopez at Sony Open in Miami|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> and [[Jo-Wilfried Tsonga]] to reach the quarter-finals. The win over Tsonga was Murray's first victory over a top-20 player since his return from surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/26741072|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beats Tsonga to set up Djokovic match in Miami|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> In the quarter-finals Murray took on [[Novak Djokovic]] for the first time since they played each other in the previous year's [[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles final|Wimbledon final]]. Murray was defeated in straight sets although the first set ended in controversial fashion with Djokovic playing a volley with his racquet over the net which the umpire allowed to stand. The defeat saw Murray slip to eighth in the world, his lowest ranking since 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/26759307|title=BBC Sport - Novak Djokovic beats Andy Murray at Sony Open in Miami|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===European clay court season===\n\n====Davis Cup Quarterfinals====\n[[Great Britain Davis Cup team|Great Britain]] faced [[Italy Davis Cup team|Italy]] in the [[2014 Davis Cup|Davis Cup]] quarter-finals. Murray defeated [[Andreas Seppi]] in his opening rubber, although the conclusion of the match was delayed until the Saturday following a rain delay.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/26901679|title=BBC Sport - Davis Cup: Andy Murray beats Andreas Seppi to bring Britain level|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> Murray then had to play again on the Saturday as he teamed up with fellow Scot [[Colin Fleming]] to defeat [[Simone Bolelli]] and [[Fabio Fognini]] in the doubles rubber and put Britain 2\u20131 up.<ref>http://www.daviscup.com/en/news/174122.aspx</ref> On the Sunday, Murray had to play his third best of five match in the space of two days as he took on Fognini in the reverse singles. The intense schedule proved too much for Murray as he was defeated in straight sets, ending his run of 19 consecutive Davis Cup singles wins which stretched back to his first appearance in the competition in 2005.<ref name=\"Italy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/daviscup/10748194/Great-Britain-dumped-out-of-Davis-Cup-by-Italy-following-defeats-for-Andy-Murray-and-James-Ward-in-Naples.html|title=Great Britain dumped out of Davis Cup by Italy following defeats for Andy Murray and James Ward in Naples|date=6 April 2014|work=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> [[James Ward (tennis)|James Ward]] then lost the decider to Seppi as Britain were defeated 3\u20132 and eliminated from the competition.<ref name=\"Italy\"/>\n\n====Madrid Open====\nMurray's first clay court tournament of the year was the [[2014 Mutua Madrid Open|Madrid Open]]. Murray opened up with a close three set victory over [[Nicol\u00e1s Almagro]],<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/27333899|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beaten by Santiago Giraldo at Madrid Masters|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> but his poor form on clay continued as he lost to qualifier [[Santiago Giraldo]] in the following round.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n====Italian Open====\nThe [[2014 Internazionali BNL d'Italia|Italian Open]] seemed to signal an upturn in Murray's fortunes. He first dismissed [[Marcel Granollers]] in straight sets,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/may/14/andy-murray-marcel-granollers-rome-open|title=Andy Murray beats Marcel Granollers in Rome Open second round|author=Kevin Mitchell|work=the Guardian}}</ref> and was then equally as clinical as he celebrated his 27th birthday with a win over [[J\u00fcrgen Melzer]] to set up a quarter-final meeting with [[Rafael Nadal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/may/15/andy-murray-jurgen-melzer-rome-open|title=Andy Murray into Italian quarter-finals with win over J\u00fcrgen Melzer|author=Kevin Mitchell|work=the Guardian}}</ref> In their first meeting since October 2011, Murray seized the early initiative and took the first set 6\u20131, but Nadal battled back to take the second. In the decider, Murray moved out to a 4\u20132 lead and was within touching distance of recording his first win over Nadal on clay. However, he was unable to see the match out and Nadal recovered to take the third 7\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/27450843|title=BBC Sport - Rafael Nadal beats Andy Murray in Italian Open quarter-final|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n====French Open====\nMurray began his [[2014 French Open|French Open]] with a four sets win over [[Andrey Golubev]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/tennis/new-coach-candidate-as-andy-murray-wins-at-french-1-3424169|title=New coach candidate as Andy Murray wins at French|work=scotsman.com}}</ref> and then defeated [[Marinko Matosevic]] to set up a third round match with [[Philipp Kohlschreiber]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/may/29/andy-murray-matosevic-french-open-second-round|title=Andy Murray storms past Matosevic in French Open second round|author=Kevin Mitchell|work=the Guardian}}</ref> The 28th seeded German proved a much tougher prospect and after Murray failed to see out the match from a commanding position in the fourth set, play was abandoned due to bad light at 7\u20137 in the deciding fifth set.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/27652035|title=BBC Sport - French Open 2014: Andy Murray match suspended due to bad light|author=Piers Newbery|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> Despite having never been beyond 7\u20135 in a decider, Murray held his nerve to take it 12\u201310 when play resumed the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/27655396|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beats Philipp Kohlschreiber at French Open|author=Piers Newbery|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> He then returned the next day to take on [[Fernando Verdasco]], but this match proved less troublesome with Murray picking up the win in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/jun/02/andy-murray-french-open-fernando-verdasco|title=This page has been removed - News - The Guardian|work=the Guardian}}</ref> In the quarter-finals, Murray played childhood friend [[Ga\u00ebl Monfils]] and stormed into a two set lead. Monfils hit back though, winning the next two to take it to a decider. Despite the momentum seeming to be against Murray, he turned the match round spectacularly to take the final set 6\u20130 and reach the semi-finals, equalling his best ever result at the French Open. The result saw him become only the 10th man to reach multiple semi-finals at all four Grand Slams and also reach a British-record 14th Grand Slam semi-final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/News/Tennis/2014/06/23/Roland-Garros-Wednesday2-Monfils-Murray.aspx|title=Andy Murray Wins In Fading Light At Roland Garros - Tennis - ATP World Tour|work=ATP World Tour}}</ref> In the semi-finals he faced [[Rafael Nadal]] for the second consecutive tournament. Nadal was at his best throughout the match and Murray struggled to keep up, weakened by the two long, five-set matches he had already played. In the end, Nadal saw off Murray in under two hours, winning comfortably in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/27734725|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beaten by Rafael Nadal in French Open semi-final|author=Piers Newbery|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Grass court season===\n\n====Queen's Club Championships====\nPrior to the grass court season beginning, Murray appointed [[Am\u00e9lie Mauresmo]] as his new coach. It was a surprise move which saw Mauresmo become the first woman to coach a high-profile male player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/tennis/no-surprise-scot-is-the-one-to-break-the-mould.24441627|title=No surprise Scot is the one to break the mould|work=Herald Scotland}}</ref> In their first tournament together, Murray recorded a straight sets win over [[Paul-Henri Mathieu]] as he attempted to defend his [[2014 Aegon Championships|Queen's Club Championship]] title. However, he suffered a shock defeat to [[Radek \u0160t\u011bp\u00e1nek]] in the following round, ending his 19 match win streak which stretched back to his [[2012 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|2012 Wimbledon]] final defeat to [[Roger Federer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/27813074|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray loses to Radek Stepanek at Queen's|author=Piers Newbery|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n====Wimbledon====\nMurray then attempted to become the first British man to defend a [[2014 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] title since [[Fred Perry]] in 1936. He began his defence with a comfortable straight sets win over [[David Goffin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/27977150|title=BBC Sport - Wimbledon 2014: Andy Murray beats David Goffin in round one|author=Piers Newbery|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> his 450th career win,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/06/23/sport/tennis/andy-murray-wimbledon-tennis/|title=Andy Murray off and running at Wimbledon, Sloane Stephens crashes out - CNN.com|author=|date=23 June 2014|work=CNN}}</ref> and followed that up with an emphatic win over [[Bla\u017e Rola]] in which he only dropped two games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28020836|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beats Blaz Rola in Wimbledon second round|author=Piers Newbery|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> His first real test was against 27th seed [[Roberto Bautista Agut]], but the Spaniard proved no match for Murray who raced to another straight sets win in just over an hour and a half.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28038906|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beats Roberto Bautista Agut at Wimbledon|author=Piers Newbery|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> Murray then defeated big serving [[Kevin Anderson (tennis)|Kevin Anderson]], the 20th seed, to reach his seventh consecutive Wimbledon quarter-final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28071971|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray beats Kevin Anderson under Wimbledon roof|author=Piers Newbery|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> His defence then came to an abrupt halt as [[Grigor Dimitrov]] ended his 17 match winning-streak at Wimbledon with a straight sets win, meaning Murray failed to reach the semi-finals for the first time since 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28110931|title=BBC Sport - Andy Murray loses to Grigor Dimitrov in Wimbledon quarters|author=Piers Newbery|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===US Open Series===\n\n====Canadian Open====\nDespite his ranking dropping to 10th after Wimbledon,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28142258|title=Andy Murray: World ranking drops to 10th - lowest since 2008|work=BBC Sport|date=3 July 2014|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref> withdrawals from [[Rafael Nadal|Nadal]] and [[Juan Mart\u00edn del Potro|del Potro]] meant that Murray was seeded eighth for the [[2014 Rogers Cup|Canadian Open]] and thus received a first round bye.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/08/01/rogers-cup-presents-tough-draw-for-novak-djokovic|title=Rogers Cup presents tough draw for Novak Djokovic|last=Shantz|first=Ian|work=Toronto Sun|date=1 August 2014|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref> Before the tournament began, Murray announced that he would be extending his partnership with [[Am\u00e9lie Mauresmo|Mauresmo]] until at least the end of the [[2014 US Open (tennis)|US Open]] but was ideally looking for a long-term deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tennis/andy-murray-looking-for-longterm-deal-with-coach-amelie-mauresmo-9647833.html|title=Andy Murray looking for long-term deal with coach Amelie Mauresmo|last=Newman|first=Paul|work=The Independent|date=4 August 2014|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> Murray also revealed that he hadn't been able to train fully earlier in the year following his back surgery last September, but had now returned to a full training schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28654658|title=Andy Murray: British number one able to train fully again|work=BBC Sport|date=5 August 2014|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> In his opening match at the Canadian Open he faced wild card [[Nick Kyrgios]], who had also been a Wimbledon quarter-finalist after upsetting Rafael Nadal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28670983|title=Andy Murray to face Nick Kyrgios in Rogers Cup in Toronto|work=BBC Sport|date=6 August 2014|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> However, Murray faced no such issues with the Australian teenager and recorded a straight sets win in just under an hour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28681076|title=Rogers Cup: Andy Murray beats Nick Kyrgios in 54 minutes|work=BBC Sport|date=7 August 2014|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref> Murray then advanced to the quarter-finals after [[Richard Gasquet]] withdrew before their third round match with an [[abdomen|abdominal]] injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28698877|title=Rogers Cup: Andy Murray faces Jo-Wilfried Tsonga in quarter-final|work=BBC Sport|date=8 August 2014|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> Murray was defeated at the quarter-final stage by eventual champion [[Jo-Wilfried Tsonga]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/tennis/2014/08/10/jo-wilfried-tsonga-beats-roger-federer-win-rogers-cup|title=Jo-Wilfried Tsonga beats Roger Federer to win Rogers Cup|website=Sports Illustrated|last=Nguyen|first=Courtney|date=10 August 2014|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> despite having been a break up in the final set.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28713089|title=Rogers Cup: Andy Murray beaten by Jo-Wilfried Tsonga in Toronto|work=BBC Sport|date=8 August 2014|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Cincinnati Masters====\nAs with the Canadian Open, Murray received a first round bye at the [[2014 Western & Southern Open|Cincinnati Masters]] as the eight seed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28748840|title=Heather Watson loses to Shuai Zhang in Cincinnati first round|work=BBC Sport|date=11 August 2014|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> He recorded a straight sets win over [[Jo\u00e3o Sousa]] in the second round,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28778183|title=Andy Murray into Cincinnati last 16 with victory over Joao Sousa|work=BBC Sport|date=13 August 2014|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> and then in the third round defeated 2013 finalist [[John Isner]] in a third set tie-break, having earlier saved two match points.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28797344|title=Andy Murray beats John Isner to reach Cincinnati quarter-finals|work=BBC Sport|date=15 August 2014|accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> He faced world No. 3 [[Roger Federer]] for a place in the semi-finals, but was defeated in straight sets. Murray had a double-break lead in the second set, but lost six of the last seven games to exit the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28813820|title=Andy Murray beaten by Roger Federer in Cincinnati|work=BBC Sport|date=16 August 2014|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref> As with the previous tournament, Murray lost to the eventual winner, with Federer going on to take the title two days later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28830641|title=Roger Federer beats David Ferrer to claim Cincinnati title|work=BBC Sport|date=18 August 2014|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n====US Open====\nMurray went into the [[2014 US Open (tennis)|US Open]] as the eighth seed, his lowest seeding at a [[Grand Slam (tennis)|major]] since [[2008 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon 2008]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/tennis/news/31234/9429980/us-open-2014-andy-murray-seeded-eighth-for-flushing-meadows|title=US Open 2014: British No 1 Andy Murray seeded eighth at Flushing Meadows|work=Sky Sports|date=20 August 2014|accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref> In the first round he faced [[Robin Haase]] where he looked to be heading for a routine straight sets victory. However, early in the third set, Murray suffered a bout of cramp and Haase was able to claw his way back into the match. It looked to be going all the way to a deciding set but Murray was able to come back from a break down to take the match in four.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28930385|title=US Open 2014: Andy Murray beats cramp to see off Robin Haase|last=Newbury|first=Piers|website=BBC Sport|date=25 August 2014|accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref> In the second round Murray defeated qualifier [[Matthias Bachinger]] in straight sets to set up a first meeting with [[Andrey Kuznetsov (tennis)|Andrey Kuznetsov]] in the third round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/28957439|title=Andy Murray beats Matthias Bachinger at US Open|last=Newbury|first=Piers|website=BBC Sport|date=29 August 2014|accessdate=30 August 2014}}</ref> He came through that encounter in four sets to set up a third meeting of the season with [[Jo-Wilfried Tsonga]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29000719|title=US Open 2014: Andy Murray beats Andrey Kuznetsov in third round|last=Newbury|first=Piers|website=BBC Sport|date=30 August 2014|accessdate=31 August 2014}}</ref> Murray won in straight sets to record his first win over a top 10 player since his [[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Men's Singles final|2013 Wimbledon final]] victory over [[Novak Djokovic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29023290|title=US Open: Andy Murray beats Tsonga to reach last eight|last=Newbury|first=Piers|website=BBC Sport|date=1 September 2014|accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref> It was Djokovic who he faced at the quarter-final stage of the tournament. In their 21st meeting the Serb proved to be too much for Murray, taking the win in four sets in a late match that lasted over three and a half hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29057887|title=Novak Djokovic beats Andy Murray to reach US Open semi-finals|last=Newbury|first=Piers|website=BBC Sport|date=4 September 2014|accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Post\u2013US Open tournaments===\n\n====Shenzhen Open====\nMurray played his first tournament after the US Open when he took a wildcard into the [[2014 ATP Shenzhen Open|Shenzhen Open]], as the second seed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/News/Tennis/2014/09/37/Shenzhen-Murray-Wild-Card.aspx|title=MURRAY AWARDED SHENZHEN WILD CARD|publisher=ATP World Tour|date=12 September 2014|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> After receiving a bye in the first round he defeated [[Somdev Devvarman]] in the round of sixteen in straight sets to set up a quarter-final meeting with [[Luk\u00e1\u0161 Lacko]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29364452|title=Andy Murray beats India's Somdev Devvarman at Shenzhen Open|website=BBC Sport|date=25 September 2014|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> Murray again won in straight sets to reach the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29378800|title=Andy Murray beats Lukas Lacko to reach Shenzhen Open semi-finals|website=BBC Sport|date=26 September 2014|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> Murray had to recover from a set down to overcome [[Juan M\u00f3naco]] and advance to his first final since winning Wimbledon the previous year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29390691|title=Andy Murray beats Juan M\u00f3naco to reach Shenzhen Open final|website=BBC Sport|date=27 September 2014|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> Murray picked up his first title of the season against [[Tommy Robredo]], coming back after being a set down once again and saving five match points in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29399228|title=Andy Murray saves five match points to win Shenzhen Open title|website=BBC Sport|date=28 September 2014|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n====China Open====\nThe following week, Murray faced [[Jerzy Janowicz]] in the first round of the [[2014 China Open (tennis)|China Open]], winning in three sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/sep/30/any-murray-defeats-jerzy-janowicz|title=Andy Murray defeats Jerzy Janowicz in China Open|website=The Guardian|date=30 September 2014|accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref> In the second round he faced [[Pablo Cuevas]], winning easily in straight sets,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/tennis/china-open-murray-beats-cuevas-to-reach-qf-1-3561062|title=China Open: Murray beats Cuevas to reach QF|website=The Scotsman|date=2 October 2014|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref> to set up a quarter-final meeting with [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] champion [[Marin \u010cili\u0107]]. Murray obtained his second top 10 win of the season with a comfortable straight sets win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29472081|title=China Open: Andy Murray defeats Marin Cilic to reach semi-finals|website=The Guardian|date=3 October 2014|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref> He then lost to world no. 1 [[Novak Djokovic]] in the semi-final in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/djokovic-downs-murray-beijing-073504102--ten.html|title=Djokovic downs Murray in Beijing|website=Yahoo sports|date=4 October 2014|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Shanghai Masters====\nMurray began the final leg of the Asian swing with a straight sets win over qualifier [[Teymuraz Gabashvili]] at the [[2014 Shanghai Rolex Masters|Shanghai Masters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/oct/07/andy-murray-teymuraz-gabashvili-shanghai-masters|title=Andy Murray downs Teymuraz Gabashvili at Shanghai Masters|website=The Guardian|date=7 October 2014|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> Murray then faced [[Jerzy Janowicz]] for the second consecutive tournament, but this match proved to be easier than their previous encounter, with Murray winning in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29534693|title=Andy Murray wins at Shanghai Masters against Jerzy Janowicz|website=BBC Sport|last=Sanghera|first=Mandeep|date=8 October 2014|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> His run was ended in third round by [[David Ferrer]], as the fifth seed recovered from a set down to beat Murray in three sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29548360|title=Andy Murray loses to David Ferrer at Shanghai Masters|work=BBC Sport|date=9 October 2014|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Vienna Open====\nIn an attempt to qualify for the [[ATP World Tour Finals|World Tour Finals]], Murray took a wild card into the [[2014 Erste Bank Open|Vienna Open]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29579174|title=Andy Murray to play in Vienna in bid to qualify for ATP Tour Finals|work=BBC Sport|date=10 October 2014|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> He defeated [[Vasek Pospisil]] in straight sets after receiving a first round bye to reach the quarter-final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29647196|title=Andy Murray eases to Vienna Open win over Vasek Pospisil|work=BBC Sport|date=16 October 2014|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref> More straight sets wins over [[Jan-Lennard Struff]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/oct/17/andy-murray-jan-lennard-struff-vienna|title=Andy Murray eases past Jan-Lennard Struff to reach Vienna semi-finals|website=the guardian|date=17 October 2014|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref> and [[Viktor Troicki]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29673687|title=Andy Murray beats Viktor Troicki to reach Vienna Open final|work=BBC Sport|date=18 October 2014|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref> followed as Murray reached the final. He once again faced [[David Ferrer]], and triumphed in three sets for his second title of the season, and the 30th of his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/10/19/tennis-men-vienna-results-idUKISS06346720141019|title=Tennis-Vienna Open men's singles final result|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Valencia Open====\nContinuing his attempt to qualify for the [[ATP World Tour Finals|World Tour Finals]], Murray entered the [[2014 Valencia Open 500|Valencia Open]] as a wild card.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/tennis/sport/story/355041.html|title=Murray ups bid to make London finals|work=ESPN|date=11 October 2014|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref> He defeated [[J\u00fcrgen Melzer]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/tennis/sport/story/359191.html|title=Murray sees of Melzer as Berdych crumbles|work=ESPN|date=22 October 2014|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref> and [[Fabio Fognini]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29744087|title=Andy Murray beats Fabio Fognini to reach Valencia Open last eight|work=BBC Sport|date=23 October 2014|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref> in straight sets to reach the quarter-finals, where he recovered from a set down against [[Kevin Anderson (tennis)|Kevin Anderson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/murray-rallies-past-anderson-valencia-142546816--ten.html|title=Murray rallies past Anderson at Valencia Open|work=Yahoo Sport|date=24 October 2014|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref> In the semi-final he faced [[David Ferrer]] for the third time in as many weeks, and won in straight sets to set up a repeat of the Shenzhen Open final against [[Tommy Robredo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29772603|title=Andy Murray beats David Ferrer to reach Valencia Open final|work=BBC Sport|date=25 October 2014|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref> Murray defeated Robredo to take the title, and, in a repeat of the Shenzhen final, had to come from a set behind and save 5 match points to prevail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/murray-outlasts-robredo-win-valencia-title-190947464--ten.html|title=Murray outlasts Robredo to win Valencia title|work=Yahoo News|date=26 October 2014|accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Paris Masters====\nAs the eighth seed, Murray received a bye in the first round of the [[2014 BNP Paribas Masters|Paris Masters]]. He opened with a straight sets win over [[Julien Benneteau]] in the second round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29820843|title=Andy Murray beats Julien Benneteau in Paris Masters|website=BBC Sport|date=29 October 2014|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> Murray then defeated [[Grigor Dimitrov]] in just over an hour to advance to the quarter-finals and seal his place at the end of season tour finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29836883|title=Andy Murray qualifies for World Tour Finals after beating Dimitrov|website=BBC Sport|date=30 October 2014|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> Murray then attempted to record his first win of the season over [[Novak Djokovic]], but it was the Serb who again came out on top in their fourth meeting, in what was also Murray's 23rd match in the space of 37 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29858134|title=Andy Murray loses to Novak Djokovic in Paris Masters|work=BBC Sport|date=31 October 2014|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n====ATP World Tour Finals====\nMurray was drawn in Group B at the [[2014 ATP World Tour Finals|ATP World Tour Finals]], along with [[Roger Federer]], [[Kei Nishikori]] and [[Milos Raonic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29885432|title=ATP Finals: Andy Murray to face Roger Federer in London|work=BBC Sport|date=3 November 2014|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> In his opening match, Murray was defeated in straight sets by Nishikori. It was his first loss to him, with Murray having won their previous three meetings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/29978145|title=Andy Murray beaten by Kei Nishikori in ATP World Tour Finals|work=BBC Sport|last=Newbery|first=Piers|date=9 November 2014|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> He bounced back in his second match, overcoming Raonic in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/30010026|title=Andy Murray beats Milos Raonic to keep ATP Finals hopes alive|work=BBC Sport|last=Newbery|first=Piers|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> Murray went into his final group match with Federer knowing that a straight sets win was required in order to reach the semi-finals. However, he was thrashed in under an hour, winning only one game, and so was eliminated - finishing third in the group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/30046849|title=Andy Murray knocked out of World Tour Finals by Roger Federer|last=Newbery|first=Piers|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==All matches==\nThis table chronicles all the matches of Murray in 2014, including walkovers (W/O) which the ATP does not count as wins. They are marked ND for non-decision or no decision.\n{{performance key}}\n\n===Singles matches===\n{{tennis sm header}}\n<!-- 2014 Qatar ExxonMobil Open -->\n{{tennis sm tournament|m=2|c=250|n=[[2014 Qatar ExxonMobil Open|Qatar ExxonMobil Open]]|l=[[Doha]], [[Qatar]]|s=Hard, outdoor|d=30 December 2013 \u2013 5 January 2014}}\n{{tennis sm match|rd=1R|m=1|o={{flagicon|QAT}} [[Mousa Shanan Zayed]] (WC)|rk=2129|rt=Win|s=6\u20130, 6\u20130}}\n{{tennis sm match|rd=2R|m=2|o={{flagicon|GER}} [[Florian Mayer]]|rk=40|rt=Loss|s=6\u20133, 4\u20136, 2\u20136|last=yes}}\n<!-- 2014 Australian Open -->\n{{tennis sm tournament|m=5|c=GS|n=[[2014 Australian Open|Australian Open]]|l=[[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]|s=Hard, outdoor|d=13 \u2013 26 January 2014}}\n{{tennis sm match|rd=1R|m=3|o={{flagicon|JPN}} [[Go Soeda]]|rk=112|rt=Win|s=6\u20131, 6\u20131, 6\u20133}}\n{{tennis sm match|rd=2R|m=4|o={{flagicon|FRA}} [[Vincent Millot]] (Q)|rk=267|rt=Win|s=6\u20132, 6\u20132, 7\u20135}}\n{{tennis sm match|rd=3R|m=5|o={{flagicon|ESP}} [[Feliciano L\u00f3pez]] (26)|rk=27|rt=Win|s=7\u20136<sup>(7\u20132)</sup>, 6\u20134, 6\u20132}}\n{{tennis sm match|rd=4R|m=6|o={{flagicon|FRA}} [[St\u00e9phane Robert]] (LL)|rk=119|rt=Win|s=6\u20131, 6\u20132, 6\u20137<sup>(6\u20138)</sup>, 6\u20132}}\n{{tennis sm match|rd=QF|m=7|o={{flagicon|SWI}} [[Roger Federer]] (6)|rk=6|rt=Loss|s=3\u20136, 4\u20136, 7\u20136<sup>(8\u20136)</sup>, 3\u20136|last=yes}}\n<!-- 2014 Davis Cup World Group : First Round -->\n{{tennis sm tournament|m=2|c=DC|n=[[2014 Davis Cup World Group|Davis Cup World Group]]|l=[[San Diego]], [[United States]]|s=Clay, outdoor|d=31 January \u2013 2 February 2014}}\n{{tennis sm match|rd=1R|rd2=R1|m=8|o={{flagicon|USA}} [[Donald Young (tennis)|Donald Young]]|rk=79|rt=Win|s=6\u20131, 6\u20132, 6\u20133}}\n{{tennis sm match|rd=1R|rd2=R4|m=9|o={{flagicon|USA}} [[Sam Querrey]]|rk=49|rt=Win|s=7\u20136<sup>(7\u20135)</sup>, 6\u2013